node.text:
ùë≥ùíêùíêùíåùíî ùíêùíá ùíçùíêùíóùíÜ 8 ‚ô°

I love to introduce my dear friend BhaÃÉvnaÃÉth. We live too far from each other to go out and drink a ChaiÃà latte. üôä Instead we love to spend time talking on the phone sharing our thoughts about life and discussing society. How we as humans act and behave, and how magical the universe actually is. I met so many 
people on my journey, but never someone like him. He is a beautiful rare soul with a very unique vision on the world. üåçüíô It’s no coincidence that I asked him for an interview about love. On Instagram I am bounded to a certain amount of character, so I will share a part here. Make sure to check my website for the whole article, will share the link in my bio. üîù
Make sure to check his site: www.bhavnath.com for more inspirational feeds. ‚ú®

As always I started the interview with the short introduction why I started with the Looks of Love and how the idea was born, followed with my famous question; “what does love mean to you?”. üíï

He became silent and answered rapidly and so sincere; “a few years ago I should have needed time to reflect on this question”. For me love is dissolving yourself with everything surrounding you. Being able to experience no sense of separation creates an ultimate feeling of freedom which is an essential element in love. When you emerge with everything you feel a deeper connection with so many things like food, music, nature, even the stars and the moon. ‚ú®üåñ
What will make you more grounded and at ease. This form of connection and freedom will make it possible for you to trust the process of life. üôåüèª

Off course self love is a fundamental key is we speak about love. You need to experience it first. How can you explain to someone how sugar tastes if you never tried it? How can you write a poem or a song about love if you were never able to feel loved? How can you share love if you don’t have a clue what it means and if you’re not capable of giving it to yourself first? ü§∑üèª‍‚ôÄÔ∏è

... to be continued on my site

node.text:
THE BACK TO SCHOOL PANDEMIC DEBATE 

This is one of the largest debates in Pandemic Recovery now and it's not really a debate at all. The problem is that we're so busy trying to defend our fears in the act of attacking each other that we've lost sight of the fact that we need to take some responsibility in making a solution possible. 

The bottom line is they're are going to have to get our children back into a learning environment but we also have to understand that it can't be the environment that we have all become formiliar with. There are ways to do this safely but we have to put the effort in the right place in order to make that happen.

If we're so focused on getting our children back in school by any means necessary the district will be under pressure to give parents what they are asking for (the reopening of school) rather than what our children need (a learning environment that has not cut corners in health and safety requirements to get them through the door).

There are very effective ways to get our children back into a learning environment where they can have face-to-face instruction where they can be in the presence of other children and they can take advantage of all of the benefits that they have become accustomed to in going to school.

Understand that while a pandemic is a school concern it is not with in their area of expertise. They're doing as well as they can be expected to without the help that they need... I encourage  school districts everywhere to REACH OUT TO EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT/BUSINESS CONTINUITY PROFESSIONALS for consultations with reference to the reopening process.

node.text:
The Sputnik - 5 vaccine proposed by Russia as a potential global saviour has more sceptics than supporters, given the limited nature of clinical trials. Our very own Bharat Biotech is working on a homegrown version of the vaccine too, as the world continues to try to curb the devastation of the raging pandemic.

I'm not sure whether we can pin our hopes on either of these breakthroughs, but being positive ain't such a bad thing either, as is apparent from my oddball take on the ensuing developments.

What does the Intelligence Communities announcement mean?  Why Did They Say The Opposite Of Trump?  https://youtu.be/HcZNBaUh-ds

The U.S intelligence Community has announced that the virus was not manmade and the genetics were not modified, however they will continue investigating. This last part left an open door and could be a sign of deep rooted changes to take place in the intelligence community. A few hours after this announcement, Trump announced that the virus was released from a lab in Wuhan and that the U.S has evidence of this and that he has seen this. He went on to say that the WHO should be ashamed; they are working like a PR agency for China. All this is proof of a history civil war taking place in American behind the scenes between agencies, departments and communities. This has also raised the questions that if the intelligence community is being run from London and the globalist elite.

node.text:
Happy to be over half way thru my goals for 2020. So far only my first race The Valentines 5k race in February has been the only in person race!
.
.
I would be lying if I said I didn't miss the start and finish line with other runners. The excitement of the crowds, the energy, the chatter about the race weather and past races and future races. The spectators and race themed finisher's  celebration. The free beer, even if I can't drink it haha. 
.
.
Yep hard not to be missing part of what drives you to run. But I had already committed to 20 races in 2020 before the Covid19 pandemic changed all of our lives. I could have just thrown in the towel and decided to set a goal for a future year and toss the 2020 goal out. But I set intention and the goal is 20 races in 2020. Not going to break my commitment. And now I am over halfway there.
.
.
My goal process may look differently now but my commitment is the same to complete those 20 races one mile at a time. Where are you keeping your commitment?
.
.
üíô Lorelei üí™üèºüëäüèº

node.text:
Pandemi corona virus telah memukul telak sektor perekonomian, hingga menyebabkan minusnya pertumbuhan ekonomi.
Bahkan, beberapa negara lain telah melaporkan bahwa mengalami resesi.
.
Pemerintah tengah berusaha menumbuhkan ekonomi¬†kuartal III 2020 guna menghindari resesi. Presiden Joko Widodo (Jokowi) pun mengakui bahwa menumbuhkan ekonomi bukan hal mudah, namun butuh kerja keras.
.
Jika ekonomi memasuki resesi, para pencari kerja di Indonesia bisa kesulitan mencari lowongan pekerjaan dalam beberapa bulan ke depan.
.

node.text:
Virus Corona atau Covid-19 telah memaksa jutaan perusahaan harus mengubah model bisnis mereka. Bahkan, yang baru memulai harus memutar otaknya untuk dapat melawan dampak ekonomi wabah tersebut.
.
Apalagi, ketika Pemutusan Hubungan Kerja (PHK) massal dan dana talangan yang mendominasi di berita, hanya sedikit orang yang berbicara tentang bagaimana rasanya memulai bisnis di kondisi saat ini. Akan tetapi, jika menurut kamu ide bisnis yang dilakukan siap untuk melangkah di tengah covid, posisikan sebagai solusi untuk kebutuhan pelanggan yang baru muncul saat ini.

node.text:
Terus gimana untuk memulai bisnisnya?
1. Cari barang atau jasa yang dibutuhkan market/ pasar
2. Pilih model usaha yang modalnya minimal, bisa dikerjakan dari rumah atau online dan ada repeat order

Beberapa Peluang Usaha yang Layak Dicoba Saat Krisis Ekonomi Menerjang:
‚úÖ Kuliner
‚úÖ Toko Kebutuhan Pokok
‚úÖ Kesehatan
‚úÖ Kecantikan

3. Ubahlah mind set kita menjadi mind set pengusaha 
.
Dalam krisis ekonomi dibutuhkan keberanian dan tekad yang kuat jika ingin memulai suatu bisnis. Namun percayalah, orang-orang yang tidak pantang menyerah, selalu bisa memanfaatkan kesempatan dan bekerja keras, akan memperoleh keuntungan besar sekalipun krisis ekonomi menghantui.

Semangat2 semuanyaaaa 
Stay safe and stay healthy yaa üòçü§ó

node.text:
S•O•S üÜò B L E N D 

This popular blend was previously only available in the ISO Boxes but as more of us turn to more natural ways of germ-busting amid this pandemic, Jade decided that the SOS Blend was a must-have for everyone.

The 5ml SOS Essential Oil Blend was inspired by those thieves from that other scary plague & includes 100% Pure Essential Oils of Clove, Lemon, Tea Tree, Cinnamon, Eucalyptus, & Rosemary. 

* Use in the shower to diffuse & inhale in the steam (2-3 drops in the corner of your shower).

* Add 4-5 drops to your diffuser to cleanse the air in the room.

* Use 25 drops in 1/2 cup of vinegar + 1 1/2 cups of distilled water in a spray bottle to use as a surface cleaner for taps, doors, common areas etc. Always spot test first.

* Dilute a drop in a tiny bit of olive oil & dab a small amount of it on your face mask before you head out (not near your nose, more near your ears). 

* Keep out of reach of children. Do not ingest or use undiluted. 

Safety is Sexy! Thanks to Donnie for his most excellent modeling, showing us how good you can look when you include the SOS Blend in your life. üòò üòâ

node.text:
Have you ever heard of "disaster capitalism"? 
.
Coined by Naomi Klein in 2007, but now pretty ubiquitous in disaster studies, it refers to a shifting of asset to already asset-rich parties who capitalise on the disruption (and opportunity) of disasters. Disaster capitalism is: governments reseizing squatter or involuntarily unoccupied land for redevelopment of high-return endeavours (HURRICANE KATRINA ANYBODY? 2004 TSUNAMI?); or the purchase of property in burst housing bubbles by real estate magnates. The list goes on. Essentially, disaster capitalism refers to the entrenching of capitalist and neoliberal systems in a state whereby the less disadvantaged are the least immobilised. 
.
I argue that disaster capitalist also refers to narrative. In a society fragmented and disrupted by an unknown and invisible threat, facing recession and austerity, the government swoops in to tighten the belt and worsen the lot for the most disadvantaged. And the narrative fits, allowing cash to take a different course that in other times may not stand the test of public opinion.
.
Every time the government comes out with another scheme that drops the cost of this pandemic and its recession onto young people and their futures, I think of disaster capitalism. And so should you.
.
Image from NUS (National Union of Students) in social media circulation.

• I keep on seeing it more and more, people talking about how low they feel about this new reality, it's only been so long but the hardest part is the reality of not knowing when this is going to stop. This could set anybody right into the quarantine depression but what can you do to fight back.üí™üèæüí™üèæüí™üèæ
•
• At the begging of this pandemic I decided to look at the positive side, you know, I'm home now, I have more time to spend with the kiddos and hubby ‚ù§  until it got me. I decided to stay in pajamas and not do a thing for 2 days, that right there set me into depression mode. As you can see the human body is designed to give it's all potential and not to sit, what I mean is you are designed to be productive in your own unique way, for example as a stylist, dressing up is my thing. I feel alive when I play with outfits and get creative by wearing a piece in different ways, for you it might be hair styling, make up, singing, reading, cooking, etc...

node.text: @tairalyn_ so needed. I know not everyone feels the same about going out. But it really does come down to doing what you feel is best and needed for your crew... And a whole freaking lot of hand sanitizer!!!

I'm so glad you did what felt right! These companies are doing everything in their power to ensure their keeping clean and i have no doubt this was best for you, your girls and also this local  usiness. ‚ô•Ô∏è
@jeno1985 thank you. It was a fun day!

@susanmgibbons yes yes! The Adventure Park there. Very impressed with all the cleaning. If anything disappointed in the few other guests. We had a not so good experience in the bumper boats with another guest (19+) targeting kids, pinning their boat in the corner, etc. My kids was yelling at then to stop, I yelled, and the staff were yelling. Not okay. Other than that, memories were made and fun was had!
@discoveringparenthood ah yes...there are always people like that out there. Ugh üò¢
Was this giggle ridge in cultus? We went there last week and were very impressed with their protocols.  Cleaning each seat after every ride.  Masks on all staff and hand sani everywhere üëç
@calleygirlcal it's all we can do. I keep thinking of the saying about not being in the same boat, but we're all in the same storm. Just trying to keep going and do our best.
Thank you so much for saying this. ‚ù§Ô∏è. We all need to do the best we can for not just the community but for our families too. And less judgment all around.

We’ve been to the water slide several times. They’ve done a really good job with COVID restrictions, we felt safe, and I needed out and a taste of normalcy for *my* mental health. No shame in it and no shaming should be happening!! Everyone is doing their best and has different thresholds.
Bumper Boats are the best! One of my best childhood memories
@shopglitterandspice.ca not busy at all. Especially during the week. They said they have not reached capacity for the limited amount on any day this summer. It was nice having little to no lines.
Mental health is so important! The kids definitely feel the effects of COVID and it’s mostly mentally. This looks like it was a blast! Was it busy there?

We’ve been in a similar situation. On the good weather days, we’ve been making an effort to go to a bigger park or the local small zoo or outdoor adventure activity places, we even went to stay an hour away from home in a static caravan for a break away. I know people are judging, but we’re not doing anything wrong, we’re being very very careful and applying, social distancing, sanitising etc.

Our kids are back to school now (Scotland) and I really didn’t want my girl not to have summer holiday fun!
@babiesnbrews it's the Cultus Lake Adventure Park. It's not a water park, but has bumper boats which are great on a hot day.
Glad you got to get out! Do you mind if I ask which water park this is?
Looks like you guys had lots of fun kids really need it üíñ
Looks like you guys had lots of fun kids really need it üíñ
@discoveringparenthood ah yes...there are always people like that out there. Ugh üò¢

Struggling.

Feeling very much like no matter what you do, you can't win.

We needed a day out as a family. For my kids mental health, we needed this. I know it's not what everyone would do. We've done a few things this summer that I know others have frowned upon. We needed this.

Things have been so stressful with back to school announcements and covid19 in general. It felt like their childhood this year was getting taken away from them.

So, we did what we felt was right. We went and had some fun at a local adventure park. While I can't go on any rides "not suitable for pregnant women", I got to see their smiles and hear the laughter. They did awesome keeping their distance. Lots of hand washing and hand sanitizer. It was the smiles and laughter that came over my kids that I will remember today.

Keep doing what you feel is best for you and your crew. Maybe that's going out somewhere. Maybe it's saying yes to going back to school. Maybe it's deciding to home school. Whatever you do and decide, trust yourself. You know your family best!

node.text: Prepare for the fall and share a message worthwhile with meaningful tees. Link in bio!

Let me tell you guys a story behind the inspiration of one of my designs:
Quarantine Can't Lock My Mind.

Quarantine took away my hard-earned opportunity of being able to leave home for a breath of fresh air on a solo date or on a hangout with friends for when life got way too overwhelming. 

It made me wonder what could I possibly do from home? Who was I if I couldn't go out to work or to college. Who am I without my friends to give me a mirror to look at? Calling up someone to talk to or chatting is very effective for some friends and has helped me tremendously, but what about the ones with whom we thrive on face-to-face social interactions? I miss them too.

I was also so lost and so hurt.

What can I *do* now? I tried cooking but that didn't give me the same reward as much as it did for my friends. I played the piano again but left when I started feeling the 'blues'.

After a long soul-searching, it hit me! I was always a creative at heart. Also, I am someone who values genuine communal bonding. Plus, I care about adding value. So, how could I combine all three? Quarantine Good Vibes was born!

Since then, I have made good progress in doing the things I care about. I am thankful that I still have my job and that classes have started online. I have also found a purpose that gives me hope and the determination to carry on. I still fumble and panic over taking a step back after taking two steps forward, and I struggle to feel grateful when I'm too down. But then, I sleep, share some of my woes with my friends, have alone time, and  feel light again. It's a battle but I'm gonna get there. 

Because no matter what, quarantine can't lock my mind. It was always up to me.

If this story touches you or you relate to it in some way, feel free to share in the comments or inbox. 
And then, if you want to remind yourself of your inner strength when lockdown times get too rough, BUY sth NOW with this design:

https://bit.ly/3294qw3

There are so many items and colors to choose from!  And so many more designs too.

Till then, take my best wishes. ‚ù§

Fall 2020 brought us a school year start unlike any other. 
.
.
My kiddos did not return to their usual classroom today. 
.
.
Instead, they embark this Fall on a distance learning/homeschool hybrid and honestly, I am so excited for them. 
.
.
This year, my children have embraced change. They have shown resiliencey and found joy in the everyday. And for all of this, I cannot be more proud of them. 
.
.
So here they are, my beautiful 6th grader, enthusiastic 1st grader and ecstatic preschooler. 
.
.
Look out world, they are determined üíöüíô
.
.

.

node.text:
Finally I get a refund. The trip was originally scheduled in March but we had to reschedule it to October as there was no option for refund back then. We were really unsure about traveling in October too, so these new options were very much appreciated. 

I’m not much of a travel bug but it’s nice to get out of this small island from time to time to experience new and exciting things. This pandemic has screwed up so many lives and the more people don’t think for one another but only for themselves, the longer we suffer. 

Thank you @flyscoot—will definitely fly with you guys soon, when that time comes. 

#lifeinthetimeofcovid19 #lifeinthetimeofcorona #scoot #travel #feelingthankful #pandemic2020

This message hit me hard today! I am tired, stressed, emotionally hanging by a thread and juggling life, (not well I should mention) as a school secretary.  Just know that teachers, nurses and administrators are feeling this even harder. Please know we are truly doing our best and giving our all to make this school year as safe and productive as possible. When we are not at school physically, (and we are there ALOT) our minds are still there. We go to bed thinking of school and it’s our first thought when we wake up. We are all in this together with this “new normal”. I will tell you though, we will Keep Going no matter what!!!! 
Sending love and positive vibes to all schools but especially to my Early Childhood Family!  YOU are all AMAZING!

Time is linear. It doesn’t stand still and it moves forward in time, always. Your friends are running in that time parallel to you and our lives may intersect again. That future is something to look forward to because it always brings new situations and new experiences that one will not have anticipated, many will inevitably be positive ones and some we can laugh about in a further future.
Hey cindyüòç, just had a quick question if you don’t mind. DM our main account @swimsuithq thanks! üëå
Hey cindyüòç, just had a quick question if you don’t mind. DM our main account @swimsuithq thanks! üëå

No bullshit. In a low. But it’s ok. We’re in a f***ing global pandemic after all with no end in sight. So, I’m allowing myself to be in the low. üåü
.
I’m not sharing this for sympathy. I’m going to say that again: I’m not sharing this for sympathy. I’m sharing this so anyone else that’s in a low can read this and know they’re not alone. üåü
.
So, if you’re feeling as shitty as me this week, just know that it will pass. But I refuse to deny my sadness and shove it down. Swallow it, suck it up and put on a smile. The American way. F**k that. I will feel it all, observe it, let it be with no shame or judgement. üåü
.
Yes I’m grateful for all the blessings that surround me. Yes I’m grateful to be healthy. Yes I’m grateful for my family and friends. But I’m also allowing myself to mourn my job. To mourn my old life. To mourn hugging people and human connection. üåü
.
I know this pandemic will eventually end....but in this present moment, it’s crappy. Tomorrow I may feel differently..who knows? üåü
.
If you’re in the sad place this week...YOU ARE NOT ALONE. I empathize with you. I understand. I feel you! I hope this post helps you, comforts you and gives you the permission you need to feel the sadness. üåü
.
Hopefully tomorrow will bring lighter feels. No emotion is permanent. üåü
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
Despu√©s de 4 meses de no pisar el hospital, tuve mi primera guardia y fue muy diferente a lo que hab√≠a vivido meses atras. 

La primer gran diferencia fue el sentimiento de miedo por poder contagiarme, y aunque iba muy bien protegido como pueden ver en la foto, esa peque√±a angustia no se fue.

La segunda diferencia fueron los pocos pacientes que pudimos ver, la "guardia tranquila" se volvi√≥ la "guardia sin aprender". Aunque lo diferente no siempre es malo, es esta ocasi√≥n fue triste.

Esperando que en algun momento todo vuelva a la normalidad, o al menos a la "nueva normalidad", solo queda cuidarnos y cuidar a nuestra familiar much√≠simo, aprender de cada cosa que hagamos lo m√°s posible y quedarnos en casa.

node.text:
ü¶ãü¶ãü¶ãü¶ã

The pandemic was a weird gift for me.
Like many things in this word it brought creation and destruction.
It’s isolation from the outside world gave space for me to truly see myself entirely. Instead of fragmented bits and pieces I have been use to.
No longer could anyone including myself hide behind a mask.
Old wounds resurfaced for a quick game of self sabotage that didn’t prevail. 
Faced to make choices on accepting what is or making changes.
Learning to love or just hold space for the dualities that exist within us.
Learning to hold space for the multitude of feelings that can be present everyday without judgment.
Learning to take things day by day and not rush ourselves or others.
Lessons in letting go of control.
Lessons in being grateful for things we were afforded in our day to day life that were temporarily put on hold.

Many things in my life changed once this weird phase in our lives started.
I could focus on the perceived bad which at points I most definitely held a little too much space for those.
But right now I choose to see it for what it gifted me personally.

node.text:
Hi. If you haven’t been keeping up with my situation here in New York City, then let me briefly tell you. So, back in march I lost my job because of the pandemic. That was really tough because I was self-employed. I spent two months trying to get my PUA (pandemic unemployment benefits) while temporarily on SNAP (welfare) because I lost my job. That was a pain, but I finally got my PUA, thank God. After that I researched and applied to a bunch of companies online. Many declined me and only two accepted my application. I chose to go with the company that I liked better. So then I got my first interview. The first interview was by phone. After that, I was asked to get interviewed again but face-to-face in a virtual setting. I did that and was told that I’ll get feedback in a day or two. When I didn’t hear back from my recruiter after two days, I sent her a follow up email asking about the postion. Later the next day she got back to me, said sorry for the delay and was waiting for more information from the hiring team. She then said that she’d call me later on today. So, I waited and waited while praying to God that I get the job, because I really like it and need it! Then around 3:30PM my recruiter called me and said I’ve got the job!!! SubhanAllah! Glory be to God! Alhamdulillah! I thanked God and then told my recruiter how happy I was to have been hired!!! So, after many months of worrying about how I was going to provide for my family and I, and after a lot of prayers and trust in the Creator, He has made a way for me. Alhamdulillah, praise be to God. 
For those of you who have been with me through this crazy time, thank you. I really appreciate your kind words, encouragement and support. If you haven’t followed me on my account @lionbeardkhannyc then I invite you to do so. I’m still doing NYC walking videos, showing you around New York City. I still plan on writing/journaling what’s going on here and with my situation. The only addition is that I post videos and goofy things here and there, and share with you more about myself. Again, thank you and thank you for reading!... A new chapter awaits and the journey continues. üï∂ - Khan

Posted @withregram • @whyyoueatinanimals_ Posted @withregram • @gillieandmarcart DEVASTATED. THIS IS ANIMAL HELL.  WHAT DO YOU THINK?
Bua Noi has woken up in the same tiny squalid cage every day for 32 years and never seen the outside world.
Despite years of campaigning by activists to have Bua Noi moved to a new home, Pata Zoo located on the 7th floor of a Bangkok shopping centre, refuses to let her go.  She rolls around on the concrete floor of her cage, pulling at tufts of hair in frustration, looking depressed, lonely and traumatised. We all know what it is like to be in lockdown but imagine that for 32 years. If there has ever been a time where we say enough is enough it must be now.
So please spread the word, the more people that know about this, the more we can save Bua Noi. See link in bio to sign the petition https://www.thepetitionsite.com/en-gb/241/056/539/inhumane-treatment-of-bua-noi-in-pata-zoo/?taf_id=65961886&cid=twitter

Finally got round to putting this wee abstract collage together today!! These are just a small selection of photos I’ve taken as a means of “recording” during lockdown here in Glasgow. Every photo pictured here has been manipulated one way or another - some more obviously so than others as I wanted to give the images a “hyper-real” or “artificial” quality, reflective of the past few months.. 
this will be available to purchase both as a collaged print and also as a series of individual prints in due course.. watch this space!

node.text: @kldscpcdaisies awww. They are so small but I look at my little ones and they are my worlds.

@diannas_doodles Yeah, in my country we have done a pretty good job of controlling the spread but there's still more to do. I think this comic is also maybe me processing that  we are not going back to normal, we are going to a new normal.

I feel the same strangely. I still go to work everyday, but it's just different. My daughter keeps me going, and I have been just looking forward towards the future! Our littles are the bright spots to this rough time ‚ô•Ô∏è
I like a lot picture nr. 3 üß†üíï
@tessacarry I absolutely love your flower photography btw!
Flowers have definitely kept me grounded too!!
@athkw thanks! The romper is from H&M baby. I shop mainly online at H&M and GAP.
Adorable. Can I ask where the romper is from?
That last picture of baby, so sweet ü•∞
@oneeksart gotta pause every now and then. üíñ

@melch.lorun soooo true about it being a theme of motherhood. Aw, I highlighted her in yellow because she is my tiny light in grey times. Also, I had originally just drawn a baby picking flowers before the comic evolved. I literally could not capture/redraw it! I tried 7 times to redraw it and then just cut out the original baby drawing and glued it on. Ahahaha.
@tiny_vice hahaha, well I love the additional highlighting and meaning the cut out gives it. Creativity through adversity. On many levels I guess, lol.

As your comics do so often, this speaks to me ‚ù§Ô∏è.

Feeling two opposite things super strongly is a major theme of motherhood for me. The anxiety and calm feels so true. Sometimes bouncing between the two feelings, and sometimes feeling both at the same time (how?! Emotions are weird). 

And the last panel with highlighted baby resonates with my soul (ugggh so cheesy but I don’t know how else to put it üòÇ). How can one tiny person be such a focus of most of my moments?

Also, love the pictures. So sweet! üòç
@rebeckys81 thanks! To the next 500! Oh god.
This is the perfect explanation for these weird times. Congratulations on 500 posts, they have all be wonderful!
@faraha30 her profile is 75% cheeks. Haha. I also find routine helps. üíñ
Them cheeks!! üòçüòçüòç‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è I don’t if I’m grounded. But yeah I guess routines and a lot of breathing exercises ‚ò∫Ô∏è

node.text:
Ok when's the last time you heard someone say something good about Iowa?‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Ya ok same. I didn't think I would utter good words about Iowa. BUT HERE I GO.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I was looking for a pandemic friendly outing in Iowa. And landed on Cedar Ridge Winery. The outdoor seating was right next to the vineyard and there were tonsss of cute IG pics taken at the spot. It looked like the perfect pandemic friendly outing! An excuse to dress up, nice ambiance, cute IG pics, what more could I want? APPARENTLY I was also allowed to want good food!!!‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
We ordered the Margherita pizza and it was SO good! The sauce was perfect, a little sweet but mostly savory. The basil was fresh. And the best part was the crust! It was SO smoky and FULL of delicious flavor. It was like eating a barbecued pizza. Ya ok I know that makes no sense, but like that's truly the best way to describe it!

node.text:
There’s always a push and pull between artists and designers to make sure the space is traversable, but also looks believable. In this one I modeled a series of broken concrete prototypes and did this image all in 3D to emulate the way the respective teams use them.  I did this with hopes that I could both satisfy designs need for clearly defined walkable surfaces, and arts need for believable breakage and higher quality modular 3D pieces.  Seems like it helped folks a bit, but it was a good exercise either way! 

.

Queer Art @queerart has recently updated their Artist Resources in Response to COVID-19! Link in their bio.

We also wanted to highlight two resources: The NYC Dancers Relief Fund (organized by @thedanceunion and 2018-2019 QAM Fellow @j_bouey ) which provides direct relief to the dance community, prioritizing NYC-based freelance BIPOC, disabled, trans/NB/GNC/queer dance artists as well as those who will not have access to emergency funds due to immigration status.
.
@translifeline provides microgrants for trans and nonbinary people to cover the costs of updating and correcting names and/or gender markers on identifying legal documents. 

.

node.text: First day of school obligatory photos! I can’t believe these two are in first grade and TK now. Sad for Livi for missing that experience of being in an actual school on her very first day of school. Kind of a crazy start though- first Lulu started complaining of a tooth ache, couldn’t log them both on, school had technical difficulties so we had to log on a different way, and after finally logging in successfully we had to catch up quick on whatever the class was doing. I was going back and forth between the two of them like a freakin DJ. I was by myself since Adrian already had his hands full. Decided to make this morning even more hectic by having them wear their school uniforms for photos. Because you know that’s importante. #firstdayofschool #pandemic2020 #tk #firstgrade #stayhome #staysafe
